==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Gondola
<hw>Gon"do*la</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It., dim. of
<ets>gonda</ets> a gondola; cf. LL. <ets>gandeia</ets> a kind of boat,
Gr. <?/ a drinking vessel; said to be a Persian word; cf. F.
<ets>gondole</ets> gondola, cup.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A long, narrow boat with a high prow and stern, used
in the canals of Venice. A gondola is usually propelled by one or two
oarsmen who stand facing the prow, or by poling. A gondola for
passengers has a small open cabin amidships, for their protection
against the sun or rain. A sumptuary law of Venice required that
gondolas should be painted black, and they are customarily so painted
now.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A flat-bottomed boat for freight.</def> <mark>[U.
S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A long platform car, either having no sides or with
very low sides, used on railroads.</def> <mark>[U. S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(A⟦eum⟧ronautics)</fld> <def>An elongated car under
a dirigible.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gondolet</ent>⟦br⟧
